As a matter of fact, we experience that certain events are invariably conjoined‚ but there is not, as in mathe- matical demmstrations, any necessity that they must be so. Invariable succession, in fact, is the highest positive notion of causality to which we can attain in the case of sensible phenomena, though this limitation does not include the moral causality of which we are conscious in volition. Necessity, however, in any sense is untenable as a logical criterion of property, since it presupposes an acquaintance with the laws of any given physical phenomena, of which the Logician as such knows nothing.
